metadata.name: Eyeshadow Roses #197
metadata.description:
"Eyeshadow Roses" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Painterly roses randomly overprinted with heavy streaks of ink. 

The roses grow by a sequence of three spirals, every new spiral smaller and superimposed on the former.  After the roses are fully formed, a random mask of heavy ink is algorithmically screened over the flowers in a pattern of horizontal or vertical lines, occasionally fully flooding the painting. The accumulation of choices evokes graffiti or printmaking. The sequence of choices are interpreted by the computer according to the algorithm. The beauty of these choices are determined by the viewer.

Each piece takes roughly 10 seconds to generate.

Artist: @sarah_ridgley
Press [s] to save the image
JavaScript / p5js | script size: 11kb

metadata.name: floating #53
metadata.description:
I spent last week at a rental bungalow in Ocean Beach (San Diego), California, for a much needed battery recharge. Most of the time, I just sat on the beach and watched the waves, and admired the different sets of circumstances that could lead to different results. I am continually bemused by how generative art is just creating algorithms to do what nature does fine on its own. 

Waves going out, waves coming in. High tide, low tide. Onshore wind, offshore wind. Strong breeze, gentle breeze. Sun is up, sun is down. Apply fxrand() to all these factors, and here we are. 

Created in p5.js.

metadata.name: Hashway 69 Revisited #49
metadata.description:
'Hashway 69 Revisited' by pixelwank
Following on from BlockonBlock, this is the evolution of that concept. 

Whether you're a Dylan or a Degen, the Hashies are for everyone. 

These give me feelings of warmth and hope or isolation & loneliness - depending on the output or my headspace at the time of viewing. 

These include a bunch of variables including:
- 23 colour palettes 
- 'dusk' or 'day' colour overlays 
- roads (%80), train tracks(15%) or paths(5%)
- clouds
- windows on the buildings & number of buildings 
- mountains 
- grasses & pond 
- moon/sun & sky texture 
& more... 

Click the image or press 's' or 'S' in live move for a 3000x3000 png 
Can look into doing even more hi-res copies for collectors in the future (I think!)

Also apologies for long loading time, my coding will get better! hehe 

This is somewhat of a culmination of the last few months learning and digging into p5js & generative art and I'm super proud of these. Thanks for collecting.
Big shoutout to all the frens at Circolors for the love and support. 
Also big shoutout to the FxHash community for being so welcoming & supportive.

R.I.F.F.
Remember It's For Fun

metadata.name: Humanoid #38
metadata.description:
Humanoids are breathing creatures that will help you calm down if you sync your breathing with them. 
Each humanoid will use 1 of 3 meditative breathing patterns that will actually relax you, go on, test it!

This project evolved out of the results I saw in Aquarium. Humanoids are my interpretation of a generative pfp project.
I'm playing with shapes and colors to see what interesting compositions occur and to see when a combination of shapes becomes more.
The backgounds change color, shifting through every color once every hour.

I hope you enjoy your Humanoid as much as I did creating them.

Press [p] to pause and play.
Press [s] to open the settings screen.

Features:
Black and white
Breathing pattern
Desaturated
Facing direction
Hollow
Neon
Outline
Type

metadata.name: simple things #130
metadata.description:
There‚Äôs beauty in simple things. Sunlight. A reflection on a puddle. The flight of a bird. Observing the clouds. Spending time with loved ones.

To celebrate the re-opening of fxhash, I'd like to contribute with some simple thing to enjoy among friends who rejoin after some time.

Simple things is a piece that is just that: simple things. Nothing fancy here. Simple circles doing simple movement, with simple colours. Maybe the viewer will rejoice in observing them transit on the screen.

It has some controls: you can press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a png file. You can set a higher resolution pressing ‚Äúd‚Äù followed by 1-9 to increase pixel density (if you get a black image, press ‚Äúd 0‚Äù and start again with a lower number). Simple controls.

It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).

The pieces exhibit simple variations: palettes, circle sizes, density of elements, backgrounds. The colours might be inverted sometimes. The direction of the movement changes also in some pieces. Some are grayscale pieces.

Just like in life, enjoying simple things is sometimes enough to leave behind the noise and our worries. Also like in life, if one wants something extra, they may get it by looking for it...

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro.
Made in p5.js, and glsl for the image controls.

metadata.name: Retrograde #23
metadata.description:
Retrograde is an original piece, a sort of space odyssey. It reminds me of the images of galaxies we see from our telescopes looking into deep space. The underlying algorithm is based on a Lissajous curve whose parameters are filled with random numbers controlling their frequency, size and opacity. Multiple curves are super-imposed to form solar systems. At intervals along each curve are circles (planets), representing instances of a celestial body in motion either forward or retrograde. 

To add to the cosmic vib there are 5 possible celestial backgrounds: 4 randomly colored color linear gradients drawn either top left to bottom right or top right to bottom left as well the possibility of solid color with a 25% chance of white. Each image generated is a fantastic galaxy of color. 

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG website @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #407
metadata.description:
‚ÄúShapes on a Plane‚Äù explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It‚Äôs intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I‚Äôd spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i‚Äôd take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I‚Äôd have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Control Room #10
metadata.description:
While playing with trigonometric functions, I stumbled upon a set of parameters that could generate the sort of grid-shaped composition you can see in the artwork. Even more interesting to me, the cells in the grid resembled old CRT screens, and through those screens, I could see faraway galaxies, subatomic worlds, sometimes rooms or corridors, plants, analog signals from some mad experiment, ... and maybe you see something else.

Or, as you can see in the animated construction, what you are seeing is just lines drawn on a vector field constructed with a sin \* cos function (plus some amplitude and scaling). Your choice.

-------------------------------------------

Original artwork by Roberto Ranon aka Doble. Made between May and June 2022 using p5.js, canvas-sketch, and love.

All primary sales are automatically redirected to KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx, a donation smart contract built by FxHash & Versum that supports various ONGs that are helping the people of Ukraine.

In full screen, pressing Cmd + S or Ctrl + S will save an image of the artwork.
